    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but I'm still a little confused about the air moving faster on top. Is it just because the path is longer, or is there something else physically forcing the air to speed up there? I've heard people mention the Coanda effect too, how does that tie into the pressure difference?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great question! The air moving faster on top of the wing is indeed due to the longer path it has to travel. This is known as the \"spanwise flow\" and is a result of the wing's curvature. The longer path means that the air molecules have to cover more distance, which causes them to spread out and move faster, creating a lower pressure area on top of the wing.\n\nThe Coanda effect, on the other hand, refers to the tendency of a fluid jet to stay attached to a convex surface. In the case of an airfoil, the Coanda effect helps to keep the airflow attached to the wing surface, which contributes to maintaining the pressure difference between the upper and lower surfaces. The curved shape of the wing helps the airflow to follow the contour of the wing, which in turn helps to create the pressure difference that results in lift. So, both the spanwise flow and the Coanda effect work together to create the lift that allows the aircraft to fly. I hope that helps clear things up a bit! Let me know if you have any more questions.",
      "source": "target",
